# Digital literacy refers to the ability to use digital devices, the internet, and online platforms safely, effectively, and responsibly. It is not limited to operating a smartphone or computer, but also includes understanding how to search for information, communicate professionally, protect personal data, and behave ethically in the digital world.

For first-time internet users from small towns, digital literacy plays a crucial role in bridging the digital divide. It helps students access educational resources, develop new skills, and build a professional online presence through platforms like email, LinkedIn, and GitHub. At the same time, digital literacy teaches safe internet practices such as creating strong passwords, avoiding online scams, and protecting privacy.

Overall, digital literacy empowers individuals to use technology with confidence, make informed decisions online, and become responsible digital citizens. It is an essential life skill for academic success, career growth, and safe participation in today’s digital society.

